rted into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."],"variants":[{"name":"Isabell","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isabelle","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , now in frequent use in the English-speaking world."]},{"name":"Isobella","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isobelle","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isobel","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Isabel ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Isabel was born in 1188, in Astley, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 2 sons with Walter de Astley. She died on 31 May 1245, in Nuneaton, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 57."},"et":{"1188–31 May 1245":"1188–31. mai 1245","1184–1240":"1184–1240","1215–1265":"1215–1265","1217–Male":"1217–Surnud","1188–1245":"1188–1245","1217":"1217","1215":"1215","about 1217":"umbes 1217","1245":"1245","1188":"1188","1265":"1265","31 May 1245":"31. mai 1245","1240":"1240","1184":"1184","Astley, Warwickshire, England":"Astley, Warwickshire, England","Hillmorton, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom":"Hillmorton, Warwickshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Nuneaton, Warwickshire, England":"Nuneaton, Warwickshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1188–31 May 1245":"1188–31. toukokuuta 1245","1184–1240":"1184–1240","1215–1265":"1215–1265","1217–Male":"1217–Kuollut","1188–1245":"1188–1245","1217":"1217","1215":"1215","about 1217":"noin 1217","1245":"1245","1188":"1188","1265":"1265","31 May 1245":"31. toukokuuta 1245","1240":"1240","1184":"1184","Astley, Warwickshire, England":"Astley, Warwickshire, England","Hillmorton, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom":"Hillmorton, Warwickshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Nuneaton, Warwickshire, England":"Nuneaton, Warwickshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1188–31 May 1245":"1188–31 mai 1245","1184–1240":"1184–1240","1215–1265":"1215–1265","1217–Male":"1217–Décédé","1188–1245":"1188–1245","1217":"1217","1215":"1215","about 1217":"environ 1217","1245":"1245","1188":"1188","1265":"1265","31 May 1245":"31 mai 1245","1240":"1240","1184":"1184","Astley, Warwickshire, England":"Ast